fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let R be a Ring. Let x\neq 0 be a nonzero element of R. We say x is:

a Left Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and xy=0;

a Right Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and yx=0;

a (Two Sided) Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq 0 and xy=0 and yx=0.
The way to remember left and right zero divisors is which side x appears.

Consider \varepsilon \in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C}) defined as
\varepsilon =\begin {pmatrix}0 & 1\\ 0 & 0\end {pmatrix}
We see that \varepsilon ^{2}=0. Hence \varepsilon  is a zero divisor.

If x is a left zero divisor, then there is a y\in  R such that xy=0. But if x were also a unit, then
\begin {align*}0&=x^{-1}0\\ &=x^{-1}(xy)\\ &=(x^{-1}x)y\\ &=1y=y\end {align*}
which contradicts the condition that y\neq 0 in the definition of a zero divisor.

(1) We can extend this to as many unknowns as we want, writing R[x_{1},…,x_{n}] or even R[x_{1},…,x_{n},…] for infinitely many unknowns. Then the sums make use of Multi-index notation. For example, for R[x,y] we have
p(x,y)=\sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha _{1}}y^{\alpha _{2}}
and so on. In fact, Dummit and Foote Abstract Algebra define (Section 9.1) R[x_{1},…,x_{n}]=R[x_{1},…,x_{n-1}][x_{n}].

Let R be a nonempty Commutative Ring. Let x_{1}, …, x_{m} be formal variables. Let
p(x) = \sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha }
be a formal polynomial, i.e., p\in  R[x_{1},…,x_{m}] with some \alpha  having |\alpha |=n being such that a_{\alpha }\neq 0. Then we define the Degree of p to be the non-negative integer \deg (p) equal to n.

(\Longrightarrow ) Assume p is irreducible and assume (a) is a proper principal ideal of R (for some a\in  R). Then
\begin {align*} (p)\subseteq  (a) &\iff  p\in (a)\\ &\iff  p=ab\hbox { for some }b\in  R\\ &\implies  a\mathrel {\bigm |} p\\ &\implies  a=pu\hbox { or }a=u\hbox { for some unit }u\in R^{\times }\end {align*}
If a=u, then (a)=R which contradicts our assumption that (a) is proper.

An Integral domain R is called a Unique Factorization Domain (or UFD for short, older texts say R is Factorial) if

Nonzero elements have a Factorization: For every nonzero element a\in R^{*} there exists a factorization
a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}
where u\in R^{\times } is a unit, p_{j}\in  R are distinct irreducitlbe elements, and n_{j}\in \mathbb {N} are positive integers; and

Factorizations are unique: For every nonzero element a\in R^{*} if there are two factorizations
a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}
and
a=v\prod ^{N'}_{j=1}q_{j}^{m_{j}}
then N=N' and there exists a permutation \sigma \in  S_{N} such that u_{j}p_{j}=q_{\sigma (j)} and n_{j}=m_{\sigma (j)} for units u_{j}\in R^{\times }.

Let R be a Unique Factorization Domain. Let a,b\in  R be elements of R. Then a and b have a Greatest Common Divisor and
\gcd (a,b)=\prod _{p	ext { irred.}}p^{\min (\mathop {\mathrm {ord}}
olimits _{p}(a),\mathop {\mathrm {ord}}
olimits _{p}(b))}
where \mathop {\mathrm {ord}}
olimits _{p_{i}}(a)=n_{i} if we can write a=u\prod _{j}p_{j}^{n_{j}} as its unique factorization, and similarly for \mathop {\mathrm {ord}}
olimits _{p_{i}}(b).

Let m,n\in \mathbb {Z} be integers. If m and n are coprime \gcd (m,n)=1, then for all a,b\in \mathbb {Z} the system of congruences
\begin {align*}x&\equiv  a\pmod {n}\\ x&\equiv  b\pmod {m}\end {align*}
has a unique solution modulo mn, i.e., \{x_{k}=x_{0}+kmn\mid  k\in \mathbb {Z}\} is the set of all possible solutions.

Let (u+I,v+J)\in (R/I)\times (R/J), we want to find x\in  R such that \varphi (x)=(u+I,v+J). Let a\in  I, b\in  J be such that a+b=1. Then x=va+ub, so we can check \varphi '(x)=(a+A,b+B). We find
\begin {align*}x &\equiv  ub\bmod {I}\\ &\equiv  (1-a)u\bmod {I}\\ &\equiv  u\bmod {I}\end {align*}
and similarly x\equiv  v\bmod {B} as desired.

Proof by contradiction. Assume for contradiction f(x) were reducible, say f(x)=a(x)b(x) in R[x] where a(x) and b(x) are nonconstant polynomials. Reducing this equation modulo P and using the assumption on the coefficients of f(x), we obtain the equation
x^{n}=\overline {a(x)b(x)}
in (R/P)[x] where the bar denotes the polynomials with coefficients reduced modulo P.

